    <h2>Ferntree Gully — Dandenong Ranges Gateway, Very Cold Winters, High Creosote Risk</h2>
    <div class="local-box"><p>Ferntree Gully sits at the base of the Dandenong National Park, stretching from the flat lower section adjacent to Boronia up into the foothills where Upper Ferntree Gully begins to climb into the ranges proper. The suburb straddles the boundary between outer suburbia and genuine mountain country, and its character reflects that position: established brick homes on the lower flat sections, and more varied, often older properties as the ground rises toward the ranges. Wood heating here is not a lifestyle choice — it is a winter necessity. Ferntree Gully regularly records some of the lowest overnight temperatures in metropolitan Melbourne during June and July, with the ranges acting as a cold reservoir that releases frigid air into the surrounding foothills on calm, clear nights. Mornings can be extremely cold, and the heating season runs from March through to November for many households. This intensive heating use over decades has two significant consequences for chimney maintenance: creosote accumulation in flue systems is faster and heavier than in warmer suburbs, and the risk of a chimney fire from ignited creosote deposits is meaningfully higher. Older homes on the upper slopes — many of which were built in the 1950s and 1960s and fitted with original open fireplaces — often have chimney systems that have never been professionally cleaned. We treat Ferntree Gully properties with this context in mind, and we assess flue condition carefully given the higher-than-average usage rates here.</p></div>
